The basic unit for analysis is the 1,2-pyrazoline ring, which has a melting point of around 100°C. The addition of a methyl group (-CH3) to the ring increases the molecular weight and size, leading to a higher melting point. The fluorine atoms (-F) in the molecule also increase the molecular weight and introduce non-polar interactions, which can also contribute to a higher melting point. The nitro (-NO2) group can also increase the melting point due to its electronegativity and ability to form hydrogen bonds. However, the presence of the oxygen atom in the 1,2-pyrazoline ring can also increase the melting point due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds. The net effect of these functional groups is an increase in the melting point of voriconazole compared to a similar 1,2-pyrazoline ring without these functional groups.
